From 1993 until 2005, the [Northamptonshire County Council](/Northamptonshire_County_Council), which saw each of the 73 [electoral divisions](/Electoral_division) across the county elect a single councillor, was consistently controlled by the Labour Party. Prior to this period, it had been operating under a state of [no overall control](/No_overall_control) since 1981, a testament to the often-divided local political landscape. The councils governing the more rural districts – specifically [Daventry](/Daventry), [East Northamptonshire](/East_Northamptonshire), and [South Northamptonshire](/South_Northamptonshire) – typically exhibited strong Conservative majorities. In contrast, the political composition of the urban districts was considerably more varied and less predictable. At the local elections held in 2003, the Labour Party experienced a significant setback, losing control of [Kettering](/Kettering), [Northampton](/Northampton), and [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough), retaining only [Corby](/Corby). Elections for the entire County Council were conducted every four years, with the last such event taking place on [4 May 2017](/2017_Northamptonshire_County_Council_election). The County Council operated under a [leader and cabinet](/Leader_and_cabinet) executive system, a common model for local authorities, and, in a move towards administrative efficiency, abolished its [area committees](/Area_committee) in April 2006.

### Economy

Main article: [History of Northamptonshire § Economy](/History_of_Northamptonshire)

Historically, the economic lifeblood of Northamptonshire flowed primarily through the manufacturing of boots and shoes, an industry that once defined the county's identity. However, this once-thriving sector experienced a precipitous decline during the [Thatcher era](/Premiership_of_Margaret_Thatcher), leading to the closure of numerous factories and, regrettably, leaving a significant portion of the county's workforce unemployed. A predictable, if painful, consequence of economic shifts. While [R Griggs and Co Ltd](/R_Griggs_Group), the venerable manufacturer of the iconic [Dr. Martens](/Dr._Martens) footwear, still maintains its UK operational base in [Wollaston](/Wollaston,_Northamptonshire) near [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough), the broader shoe industry has, by and large, suffered a profound decline as manufacturing operations have steadily migrated away from England. In the mid-19th century, the region boasted over 2,000 shoemakers; today, that number has dwindled to a mere 30 or so, a stark reminder of industrial evolution.

Despite this decline, Northamptonshire's economy has diversified. Large employers now include the breakfast cereal giants [Weetabix](/Weetabix), whose operations are based in [Burton Latimer](/Burton_Latimer), and the [Carlsberg](/Carlsberg_Group) brewery, a significant presence in [Northampton](/Northampton). Other notable companies providing substantial employment opportunities are [Avon Products](/Avon_Products), the [Nationwide Building Society](/Nationwide_Building_Society), [Siemens](/Siemens), [Barclaycard](/Barclaycard), [Saxby Bros Ltd](/Saxby_Bros_Ltd), and [Golden Wonder](/Golden_Wonder). In the western part of the county, the [Daventry International Railfreight Terminal](/Daventry_International_Railfreight_Terminal) (DIRFT) stands as a major hub, a crucial rail freight terminal strategically located on the [West Coast Main Line](/West_Coast_Main_Line) near [Rugby](/Rugby,_Warwickshire). [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough) also contributes to the logistics network with a smaller railfreight depot situated on Finedon Road, known locally as Nelisons sidings.

